passages.text: F3Q25 review: In- line quarter PC refresh, outlook lowered on Print
HPQ 12m Price Target: \(28.00 Price:\) 27.11 Upside: \(3.3\%\)

HPQ's F3Q25 EPS of \(0.75 was in- line with GS/consensus of\) 0.75/\\$0.75 driven by a Personal Systems EBIT beat offset by softer Print EBIT margins. Within Personal Systems, HPQ grew revenue \(+6\%\) yoy with \(+5\%\) growth in units driven by share gains in commercial (Windows 11 refresh) and premium consumer (particularly in North America and China on back- to- school). HPQ expects to see continued momentum in PC refresh into next year (MSD% industry unit growth in C2H25, growth in 2026) with over \(\sim 50\%\) of installed base converted to Windows 11, as well as continued AI PC adoption. The company guided F4Q25 PS revenue to grow similar to last year \((+2\%\) qoq v. consensus \(+3\%\) ) with margins solidly in- line with HPQ's target range \((5 - 7\%)\) . Within Print, revenue declined \(4\%\) yoy with softer demand in office against a competitive pricing environment, though home and supplies performed as expected & the company delivered strong growth in strategic areas including subscriptions & industrial graphics. HPQ guided for F4Q25 Print growth in line with last year \((+7\%\) qoq v. consensus \(+8\%\) ) with margins at the top end of HPQ's target range \((16 - 19\%)\) , reflecting higher supplies volume & a focus on profitable units. The company expects the broader print market to decline LSD% in 2025 and 2026. Relative to last quarter \((\) 0.12\(unmitigated tariff impact), HPQ was able to mitigate the majority of tariff costs in F3Q with nearly all US products now produced outside of China. HPQ will host an Investor Day in early 2026 including updates on long term targets. HPQ's F4Q25 EPS guidance of\) 0.87- \$0.97 implies full year EPS of \(3.06 - 3.16,\) 0.04 lower at the midpoint prior FY guidance for \(3.00 - 3.30\) of EPS, driven by a more cautious view on P1. Key takeaways: Continued PC demand strength amidst ongoing refresh.

During the quarter, Personal Systems revenue grew \(6\%\) yoy (v. \(8\%\) yoy in F2Q25), driven by \(5\%\) yoy PC unit shipment growth and \(1\%\) (implied) ASP growth yoy. Within Commercial, units grew \(3\%\) yoy driven by continued Windows 11 refresh activity, AI PC adoption, and share gains in the commercial premium category. Notably, HPQ estimates over \(30\%\) of its installed base has refreshed to Windows 11 to- date, and \(\sim 25\%\) of its \(25\) PC shipments consisted of AI PCs. Within Consumer, units grew \(8\%\) yoy, simply accelerating from \(- 2\%\) yoy in F2Q25 driven by back- to- school purchasing activity and share gains in the consumer premium category. On a forward basis, HPQ expects the PC market to grow MSD% yoy in C2H25 on continued Windows 11- driven refresh and adoption of AI PCs, particularly as greater AI applications are rolled out by software providers. Windows 11 refresh should continue to be PC demand driver in 2026. As such, HPQ expects Personal Systems F4Q25 revenue to grow in- line with prior year seasonality \((+2\%\) qoq), implying \(+6\%\) yoy growth, benefiting from continued PC refresh & AI PC adoption within commercial segments, as well as holiday purchases and back- to- school purchases in consumer segments.

Personal Systems EBIT margins of \(5.4\%\) return to long- term \(5 - 7\%\) range, and should continue to benefit from pricing actions. F3Q25 Personal Systems margins of \(5.4\%\) improved from \(4.5\%\) in F2Q25. First, improved Personal Systems margins were driven by greater mix of premium products including AI PCs, premium commercial (where HPQ believes it gained share), and premium consumer. Second, HPQ benefited from selective price increases. For F4Q25, HPQ expects Personal Systems margins to improve sequentially from \(5.4\%\) , supported by greater seasonal holiday volumes, continued benefits from prior pricing actions, and cost management, offsetting trade- related costs.

Print softness on challenged office hardware demand and competitive pricing. During the quarter, Print revenue declined \(- 4\%\) yoy. HPQ notes that office demand was slightly lower than expected (particularly in North America and Europe) as customers temporarily prioritize investments in AI and PC refresh over Print hardware and supplies. Additionally, the company saw continued pricing pressure from competitors. Within its key growth categories, HPQ saw DD% yoy growth in consumer subscriptions and DD% yoy hardware growth within its Industrial Print business. On a forward basis, HPQ expects the Print market to decline LSD% yoy in both 2025 and 2026, though it will prioritize maintaining profit margins through (a) focus on its key growth areas including its consumer subscription and industrial print businesses; (b) gaining share in higher value office categories; and (c) cost discipline. For F4Q25, HPQ expects Print revenue to be in- line with prior- year seasonality \((+\) \(- 7\%\) qoq), implying \(- 4\%\) yoy decline, and EBIT margins to be near the top of its \(16 - 19\%\) long- term target range, supported by higher Supplies revenue mix and disciplined pricing and cost management, offsetting trade costs.

Future Ready Savings Plan progressing as planned. HPQ states it is on track to achieve \(\) 2\(bn in cumulative gross annualized savings by the end of F2025 (in- line with F2Q25 expectations) driven by greater company efficiency through using AI internally to drive process automation and optimization. The company believes savings from this plan will both allow HPQ to (a) mitigate macro uncertainty; and (b)

continue to invest in key growth areas. For example, though HPQ estimates it was able to mitigate the majority of tariff related costs in F3Q25 through manufacturing diversification, cost reductions, and pricing adjustments, it plans to continue to ramp production in Vietnam, Thailand, Mexico, and the US.
HPQ's F3Q25 EPS of \(0.75 was in- line with GS estimates/FactSet Consensus\) 0.75/\(0.75 and guidance of\) 0.68- 80.
HPQ's F3Q25 revenue of \(13,932 mn beat GSe/consensus\) 13,838/\$13,691 mn with:

- Personal Systems Group revenue of \(9,931 mn beat GS/consensus of\) 9,746/\$9,561 mn, with units up \(+5\%\) yoy (v. GSe of \(+3\%\) yoy). Consumer PS net revenue was up \(8\%\) yoy (units up \(8\%\) yoy) and Commercial PS revenue was up \(5\%\) yoy (units \(+3\%\) yoy).- Printing revenue of \(3,986 mn was in-line with GSe/consensus\) 4,092/\$3,999 mn, with total units down \(-9\%\) yoy (Consumer Printing units down \(-8\%\) yoy; Commercial Printing units down \(-12\%\) yoy). Supplies revenue was \(2,604 mn\) (v. GSe/consensus \(2,649 mn\) /\(2,562 mn).
Gross profit of \(2,851 mn was just above GSe\) 2,768 mn and consensus \(2,798 mn\) .

Non- GAAP EBIT of \(995 mn was in- line with GSe/consensus\) 1,003 mn/\$1,001 mn. Personal System Group EBIT of \(541 mn\) (5.4% margins) was in- line with GS estimate of \(517 mn\) (5.3%) and Printing EBIT of \(689 mn\) (17.3%) was below GS estimates of \(736 mn\) (18.0%).

HPQ provided guidance for F4Q25 including: (1) GAAP diluted EPS of \(0.75 - 0.85; (2) Non- GAAP diluted EPS of\) 0.87- \$0.97 (v. consensus of \$0.92); (3) Personal Systems revenue to be in- line with prior year seasonality (+2% qoq v. consensus +3%); (4) Personal Systems margins to be solidly within 5- 7%, improving sequentially; (5) Print revenue to be in- line with prior year seasonality (+- 7% qoq v. consensus +8%); and (6) Print EBIT margins to be near the top of HPQ's target 16- 19% range, improving sequentially.

For F2025, HPQ reiterated its expectation for free cash flow between \(2.6 - 3.0 bn\) for F2025. By segment, HPQ expects (1) the PC market will grow by MSD% yoy in F2H25, and should continue to grow in F2026; and (2) the Print market to decline LSD% yoy in 2025, and at a similar level in 2026.

Valuation. We are Neutral- rated on HPQ with a 12- month updated target price of \(28 (v.\) 26 prior) based on 7.5X (unchanged) our NTM+1Y revised EPS forecast.

Key risks include: (- ) Increases in hybrid work or slower- than- expected consumer demand could result in worse- than- expected revenue for commercial PC demand; Pricing pressure driven by high levels of industry channel inventory, declining component costs, and higher discounting could result in lower- than- expected margins; increase in the number of corporate layoffs could result in lower demand for new commercial PCs; (+ ) Supplies execution by a mix shift towards margin accretive hardware, such as Big Tank, and ink subscription services could result in better margins; Better- than- expected demand for gaming PCs, peripherals, or video conference tools (including benefits from Poly) may result in better- than- expected revenue.

Investment thesis summary. HPQ is a global manufacturer and supplier of PCs, printers, and related supplies and services. In our view, HPQ's forward growth will be impacted by (1) softer near- term industry PC unit demand following pandemic benefits,

excess channel inventory and pricing pressure. That said, industry PC demand may benefit from the eventual replacement cycle for PCs installed at the onset of the pandemic (e.g., a 3- year aged installed base), while HPQ's focus on higher end PCs may provide it a differentiated portfolio that should outperform the industry; (2) Printing headwinds across commercial and consumer markets, reflecting headwinds from hybrid work, which reduces in- office printing requirements, and competition in consumer. That said, we're encouraged by HPQ initiatives that should mitigate secular headwinds to commercial and consumer printing through its focus on higher- margin hardware such as Big Tank (e.g., includes a large tank of ink) and \(\mathsf{HP}+\) (e.g., a smart printer that serves as an effective top- of- funnel for ink subscription services), as well as ink subscription services; and (3) a capital allocation policy should be supportive of return of capital to shareholders. We expect HPQ to still return \(40 - 80\%\) of FCF to shareholders in the form of dividends and buybacks over the next several years.

The Goldman Sachs Factor Profile provides investment context for a stock by comparing key attributes to the market (i.e. our universe of rated stocks) and its sector peers. The four key attributes depicted are: Growth, Financial Returns, Multiple (e.g. valuation) and Integrated (a composite of Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple). Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple are calculated by using normalized ranks for specific metrics for each stock. The normalized ranks for the metrics are then averaged and converted into percentiles for the relevant attribute. The precise calculation of each metric may vary depending on the fiscal year, industry and region, but the standard approach is as follows:

Growth is based on a stock's forward- looking sales growth, EBITDA growth and EPS growth (for financial stocks, only EPS and sales growth), with a higher percentile indicating a higher growth company. Financial Returns is based on a stock's forward- looking ROE, ROCE and CROCI (for financial stocks, only ROE), with a higher percentile indicating a company with higher financial returns. Multiple is based on a stock's forward- looking P/E, P/B, price/dividend (P/D), EV/EBITDA, EV/FCF and EV/Debt Adjusted Cash Flow (DACF) (for financial stocks, only P/E, P/B and P/D), with a higher percentile indicating a stock trading at a higher multiple. The Integrated percentile is calculated as the average of the Growth percentile, Financial Returns percentile and (100% - Multiple percentile).

Financial Returns and Multiple use the Goldman Sachs analyst forecasts at the fiscal year- end at least three quarters in the future. Growth uses inputs for the fiscal year at least seven quarters in the future compared with the year at least three quarters in the future (on a per- share basis for all metrics).
For a more detailed description of how we calculate the GS Factor Profile, please contact your GS representative.

Across our global coverage, we examine stocks using an M&A framework, considering both qualitative factors and quantitative factors (which may vary across sectors and regions) to incorporate the potential that certain companies could be acquired. We then assign a M&A rank as a means of scoring companies under our rated coverage from 1 to 3, with 1 representing high (30%- 50%) probability of the company becoming an acquisition target, 2 representing medium (15%- 30%) probability and 3 representing low (0%- 15%) probability. For companies ranked 1 or 2, in line with our standard departmental guidelines we incorporate an M&A component into our target price. M&A rank of 3 is considered immaterial and therefore does not factor into our price target, and may or may not be discussed in research.
